comments.content:
LEFT JOIN with a NULL check is the classic approach:

SELECT DISTINCT p.user_id FROM page_views p LEFT JOIN page_views s ON p.user_id = s.user_id AND s.page = 'signup' WHERE p.page = 'pricing' AND s.user_id IS NULL;

But I prefer the EXCEPT or NOT EXISTS pattern — reads more like the business requirement.

NOT EXISTS is usually fastest:

SELECT DISTINCT user_id FROM page_views pv WHERE page = 'pricing' AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM page_views WHERE user_id = pv.user_id AND page = 'signup');

The optimizer can short-circuit as soon as it finds one signup row. LEFT JOIN has to build the full join first.

WHERE runs BEFORE GROUP BY. You can't filter on aggregates in WHERE because the groups don't exist yet. You need HAVING, which runs AFTER GROUP BY.

SELECT department, COUNT(*) AS emp_count FROM employees GROUP BY department HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;

WHERE filters rows. HAVING filters groups. Tattoo this on your forearm.

